description: From Latin appropinquare (“to approach”), present active infinitive of appropinquō, from ad- ("towards") + propinquō (“draw near”), verbalization of propinquus (“near”); compare prope ("near").

verbs.description: appropinquate (third-person singular simple present appropinquates, present participle appropinquating, simple past and past participle appropinquated)

entries.meaning: (rare, literary, transitive, intransitive) To approach; to near.
examples: The factor invoked by Kalecki to rationalize the phenomenon, however, appropinquates Sraffa's observations on capital markets.
